		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Polyphasic sleep</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Polyphasic sleep</b>, a term coined by early 20th century psychologist J.S. Szymanski,<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> refers to the practice of <a href="/wiki/Sleep" title="Sleep">sleeping</a> multiple times in a 24-hour period—usually, more than two, in contrast to biphasic sleep —and does not imply any particular schedule. See also <a href="/wiki/Segmented_sleep" title="Segmented sleep">Segmented sleep</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sleep#Optimal_amount_in_humans" title="Sleep">Sleep (Optimal amount)</a>. The term <i>polyphasic sleep</i> is also used by an online community which experiments with ultra-short napping to achieve more time awake each day.</p>
